a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20025.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Start over?</span><hr size=1> The thought makes me cringe, really.  I play a 49 iksar shaman, 57 gnome wizard and a 55 human monk.  The monk was first, the wizard my favorite.  The shaman gets played if I want to feel contempt for my opponents.  The shaman is the most versatile.  He is the best one on one soloer AND the one most likely to get a group when he wants, not to mention the easiest epic.<br>
<br>
Starting from scratch, I would likely do a shaman, although not necessarily an iksar.  The road with the wizard seemed long and lonely (no, I didn't go looking for groups either, I was just in the frame of mind when I played him usually), while the shaman was constantly busy with cannibalize, rebuffing, the pet, tanking, etc.  In other words, he was more occupying to solo than the wizard, who pretty much medded to full, then either root-nuked or snare kited for the kill, then sat and medded for 3 bubbles of mana.  The shaman was also able to drop mobs consistently 2 to 3 levels before the wizard and even further in advance of the monk.<br>
<br>
So, shaman for power and involvement while soloing, and a much desired grouping character when I want to be social.<br>
<br>
Understand that the wizard is now my favorite at this point.  However, for a long time he was the character I logged onto when I wasn't feeling like playing seriously but still wanted to watch guild chat as I read a book.  It wasn't the mid 40s when he started becoming more than that, and not until 51 with the ability to quad with distintion that he really took off for me.<br>
<br>
Vorkreider<br>
